[2] Taiwan
Date: Fri 23 Jul 2010
Source: Taiwan Headlines [edited]
<http://www.taiwanheadlines.gov.tw/ct.asp?xItem=197617&CtNode=39>


The Department of Health (DOH) said Friday [23 Jul 2010] that the
number of recorded indigenous dengue fever cases has risen to 12,
mostly in the southern city of Kaohsiung. Chou Chih-hao, Deputy
Director-General of the DOH's Centers for Disease Control, said that
among the 12 cases, 11 were reported from the city's Gushan District,
while the most recent was found in Kaohsiung County's Fongshan City.
The latest patient is a 12-year-old boy who started displaying
symptoms 12 Jul [2010] and was confirmed as the 12th indigenous dengue
fever case on 20 Jul [2010].

The DOH warned the public to take precautions against dengue fever, as
the disease is entering its peak season. Because no vaccine exists for
the disease, the DOH said the most effective measure that can be taken
is to eliminate potential breeding grounds for the mosquitoes by
cleaning up containers of standing water.

