[6] USA (Florida)
Date: Wed 21 Jul 2010
Source: WESH.com [edited]
<http://www.wesh.com/health/24343521/detail.html>


Dengue fever has infected a handful of people in Central Florida,
health officials said. Health officials said more than a dozen people
have picked up the virus from mosquitoes in the [Florida] Keys. More
than 30 more across the state of Florida have the fever after picking
it up out of the country.

Mosquitoes in central Florida do not carry dengue [virus], but they
could if people are not careful, local doctors said. Mosquito control
experts are treating areas near where 3 Orange County people have
dengue. While the patients caught the fever somewhere else, if they
get bitten by mosquitoes, the virus could get into the local mosquito
population. "There's a possibility that you've produced enough virus
for our local mosquitoes to pick it up," said Dr. Tom Breaud with
Orange County Mosquito Control.

Doctors say anyone with dengue should stay inside, away from
mosquitoes. While most mosquitoes bite at dawn and dusk, insects
carrying dengue [virus] have a different pattern. "The mosquitoes that
transmit dengue [virus] to us bite during the day," said Breaud.

