[9] Honduras
Date: Tue 20 Jul 2010]
Source: Proceso Digital [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
<http://proceso.hn/2010/07/20/Salud+y+Sociedad/Serotipo.del.virus/25906.html>


According authorities of the hospital centers in Honduras, a "more
aggressive" dengue [virus] serotype is circulating in the country and
is what caused most of the recent deaths from the hemorrhagic variant
[DHF].

Jorge Melendez, head of the Department of Pediatrics at the Maternal
and Infant Teaching Hospital Center, explained that the _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquito transmits 4 different serotypes of the dengue virus:
1, 2, 3, and 4. Serotypes 1, 3 and 4 have been circulating widely in
the country, but "at this time, Hondurans face serotype 2, which has
the distinction of being more aggressive [virulent], so one would be
observing the severe clinical pictures [seen] over the last few days,"
said Melendez. The physician said that many times, "the apparently
healthy patient arrives, and in a short time, we see a sharp decline
in their health condition, which often leads to shock and frequently
is irreversible, putting life at risk." Only this weekend in the
Maternity and Infants (Hospital) in Tegucigalpa, at least 50 children
were admitted with symptoms that were reasonably similar to DHF," said
Melendez.

President Porfirio Lobo Sosa, at the Monday [19 Jul 2010] meeting of
the Council of Ministers, established the National Front for the Fight
Against Dengue, which will coordinate activities with the Secretariat
of Health and the inhabitants of the communities most affected, among
these Tegucigalpa and San Pedro Sula.

Elements of the Honduran Army also have dispersed to different
neighborhoods of the capital city, where they carry out fumigation and
clean up to eradicate the mosquito that transmits dengue [virus].

To date, the authorities of the Secretariat of Health have registered
22 406 cases of classical dengue, 705 of DHF, of which 23 deaths have
been certified.

