[10] El Salvador
Date: Mon 19 Jul 2010
Source: SDP Noticias [in Spanish, trans. Corr.SB, edited]
<http://sdpnoticias.com/sdp/contenido/2010/07/19/4/1080898>


The Ministry of Health of El Salvador announced today [19 Jul 2010]
that in the coming period, a national campaign will be launched, to
prevent an epidemic of dengue which in recent weeks has seen an
increase in cases.

The Director of Surveillance of the Ministry of Health, Julio Armero,
told reporters that the work will be undertaken from Friday through
next Sunday [23-25 Jul 2010], and homes will be searched to clean up
the breeding sites of _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes, the vectors of
dengue [virus]. "The concern is the number of closed houses or poor
collaboration in cleanup actions," said Armero.

The increase in dengue cases so far this year [2010] seems to indicate
that an epidemic will continue for the remainder of July, August and
September 2010, during the rainy season, which helps to increase
mosquito breeding sites.

Until last week, 6197 confirmed cases of dengue were reported, of
which 96 are DHF.

The campaign consists of massive fumigation in various parts of the
country, delivery of chemical larvicide known as "Abate," so that
families can protect clean water [from mosquito breeding]. Talks for
awareness will be other major actions that will be promoted during the
3-day work for prevention and clean up.

"We do not want dengue to increase considerably higher," the official
said, explaining that the population most affected by the disease is
located in the municipality of Metapan in the western department
[state or province] of Santa Ana.

