[11] Brazil (Pernambuco)
Date: Wed 21 Jul 2010
Source: JC Online [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://jc.uol.com.br/canal/cotidiano/saude/noticia/2010/07/21/avanco-da-dengue-deixa-upas-com-superlotacao-229395.php>


Among the 300 [people] who daily seek treatment in the Immediate Care
Units (UPA) in Paulista and Olinda, in Grande Recife, the proportion
of these people with symptoms of dengue reached 70 percent. Because of
the overload, coordinators of UPA Paulista do not rule out the
possibility of returning to suspension of attention to new adult
patients, as occurred on Monday night [19 Jul 2010]. We have
reinforced the group of physicians on duty at night, but the demand
[for attention] increased, and we cannot count on the municipal
[health] network," said UPA Coordinator, Vania Brayner.

According to her, in addition to new patients, those of the previous
day return to monitor their platelets (an indicator of increasing
seriousness of dengue [virus infection]). This great demand has
[caused] congestion in the laboratory of the Metropolitano Norte
Miguel Arraes Hospital. "The ideal would be for these patients to be
monitored by attention from basic municipal [health care]," she said.

